<!-- Begin Title -->
<h1>Continued Fraction</h1>
<!-- End Title -->
<hr class=3D"margin-t-1-8 margin-b-3-4">
<!-- Begin Total Content -->
<div class=3D"attachments text-align-r">
<a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/notebooks/NumberTheory/ContinuedFr=
action.nb" download=3D"ContinuedFraction.nb"><img src=3D"https://mathworld.=
wolfram.com/images/entries/download-notebook-icon.png" width=3D"26" height=
=3D"27" alt=3D"DOWNLOAD Mathematica Notebook"><span>Download
 <span class=3D"display-i display-n__600">Wolfram&nbsp;</span>Notebook</spa=
n></a>
</div>
<!-- Begin Content -->
<div class=3D"entry-content">
<p>
The term "continued fraction" is used to refer to a class of expressions of=
 which <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/GeneralizedContinuedFractio=
n.html">generalized continued fraction</a>
 of the form
</p>
<div>
<table summary=3D"" width=3D"100%" align=3D"center" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0" style=3D"padding-left: 50px">
<tbody><tr><td align=3D"left"><img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/ima=
ges/equations/ContinuedFraction/NumberedEquation1.svg" class=3D"numberedequ=
ation" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"126" =
height=3D"105" alt=3D" b_0+(a_1)/(b_1+(a_2)/(b_2+(a_3)/(b_3+...)))=20
 =3Db_0+K_(n=3D1)^infty(a_n)/(b_n)   "></td></tr>
</tbody></table>
</div>
<p>
(and the terms may be integers, reals, complexes, or functions of these) ar=
e the most general variety (Rocket and Sz=C3=BCsz 1992, p.&nbsp;1).
</p>
<p>
Wallis first used the term "continued fraction" in his <i>Arithmetica infin=
itorum</i> of 1653 (Havil 2003, p.&nbsp;93), although other sources list th=
e publication date
 as 1655 or 1656. An archaic word for a continued fraction is anthyphaireti=
c ratio.
</p>
<p>
The <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/SimpleContinuedFraction.html">=
simple continued fraction</a> takes <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.c=
om/images/equations/ContinuedFraction/Inline1.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" =
style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"46" height=
=3D"21" alt=3D"a_n=3D1"> for all <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/=
images/equations/ContinuedFraction/Inline2.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" sty=
le=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"9" height=3D"21=
" alt=3D"n">, leaving
</p>
<div>
<table summary=3D"" width=3D"100%" align=3D"center" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0" style=3D"padding-left: 50px">
<tbody><tr><td align=3D"left"><img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/ima=
ges/equations/ContinuedFraction/NumberedEquation2.svg" class=3D"numberedequ=
ation" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"227" =
height=3D"61" alt=3D" b_0+1/(b_1+1/(b_2+1/(b_3+...)))=3Db_0+K_(n=3D1)^infty=
1/(b_n). "></td></tr>
</tbody></table>
</div>
<p>
If <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/ContinuedFrac=
tion/Inline3.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-widt=
h:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"16" height=3D"22" alt=3D"b_0">
 is an integer and the remainder of the <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfra=
m.com/PartialDenominator.html">partial
 denominators</a> <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equation=
s/ContinuedFraction/Inline4.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-heigh=
t:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"16" height=3D"21" alt=3D"b_k">
 for <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/ContinuedFr=
action/Inline5.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-wi=
dth:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"37" height=3D"21" alt=3D"k&gt;0">
 are positive integers, the continued fraction is known as a <a href=3D"htt=
ps://mathworld.wolfram.com/RegularContinuedFraction.html">regular
 continued fraction</a>.
</p>
<p>
The most successful algorithm employed by the Ramanujan Project (Raayoni <i=
>et al. </i>2021) relied on a brute-force search over the space of polynomi=
al continued fractions
 to find new formulas for mathematical constants. Elimelech <i>et al. </i>(=
2023) subsequently
 used algorithm involving <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Factoria=
lReduction.html">factorial reduction</a>
 to search for new polynomial continued fraction formulas, discovering hund=
reds of
 new formulas for mathematical constants, including <img src=3D"https://mat=
hworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/ContinuedFraction/Inline6.svg" class=3D=
"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=
